snippet.title: Create a Ragdoll in 100 Seconds! And make it shootable!
snippet.description:
Ragdoll explaination: 0:44
Shoot/Activate Ragdoll: 3:30

Yes, this is a video for a short introduction in Unity for ragdolls. Ragdolls are a great way to plug your player out of the matrix and let it fall as if it was dead. This time I will use Unity's build in Ragdoll Component. I personaly do not like it that much, but it is doing what it is supposed to do. You can find this type of tutorial all over youtube, but many are missing the activation/deactivation.

This was just the start for ragdolls. In the next video I will create a custom ragdoll from scratch to apply it to custom objects, like animals and all kind of creatures. Make sure to subscribe: https://www.youtube.com/c/DitzelGames?sub_confirmation=1

snippet.title: How To Make an Active Ragdoll Controller in Unity (My method) | Part 1 - Setting up the ragdoll
snippet.description:
This is my very first time recording a tutorial video, as you can probably tell by all the screw-ups I've done throughout the video.

In this vid I'll be showing you how set up an active ragdoll using the Unity game engine. I've used some made up terms that not everyone will understand in the video, so I'll explain them...

- faint : basically when the ragdoll is in full ragdoll mode.
- toDef(Boolean) : for the damper value of the spring joint, the default damper value for spring joints is 0,2f.
- returning : when the ragdoll is going back into non-ragdoll mode.

The "Joint" script - https://www.mediafire.com/file/n7o3dvfwonalj7u/Joint.cs/file

In the next part I'll (hopefully) be completing the ragdoll controller.

If you have any questions or something is wrong then let me know.

My itch.io account - https://greyseth.itch.io

snippet.title: Spring Bones in Unity (Bouncing Hair) [2/2]
snippet.description:
Character hair / cloth physics setup using Spring Bone script in Unity. This allows different parts of the model (eg, hair, coat, long shirt or skirt) to simulate cloth-like or bouncing behavior when the character moves.
This is more of an introduction to the basic setup. 
Will dive deeper into advanced setup in future videos, eg. dealing with issues of character legs going through the cloth.
So stay tuned for more!

The Spring Bones script is a feature that is part of the Unity-Chan Toon Shader 2.0 package, which I am using for this project. Information on this shader (in English) can be found here:
https://connect.unity.com/p/unity-chan-toon-shader-ver-2-0

This is the official website for Unity-Chan:
http://unity-chan.com/
All credits of the shader goes to them.

Link to Part 1:
https://youtu.be/cX_y9xkRCOs

snippet.title: The right way to do movement in Unity!
snippet.description:
Hey everyone,
in this video, I show you the right way to do movement int Unity.
I explain the difference between using the Transform and using the Rigidbody and why is the Rigidbody better.

Correction:
Instead of
 new Vector3 (xMove, rb.velocity.y, zMove)*speed*Time.deltaTime 
write
 new Vector3 (xMove*speed, rb.velocity.y, zMove*speed)*Time.deltaTime
